        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@dundargoc I framed this poorly. My intent was not that `windows-latest` changes the runner today. The idea was:\r\n\r\n- `windows-latest` currently aliases `windows-2025` (as zeertzjq said, this is indeed a no-op today)\r\n- i made #39764 to test the upcoming VS2026 image - it worked\r\n- _after_ the upcoming migration migration, both `windows-2025` and `windows-latest` move together\r\n- `windows-latest` image is in better condition now\r\n- *so* (and this is why I put this up, despite missing the edit to `maintain.md`): move to `windows-stable` *now* (this is a policy-changing decision). The next upgrade will work as proven, and given its stability according to yourself, we can just continue to upgrade automatically in the future just fine.\r\n\r\nDoes that match the `maintain.md` change you had in mind? Just looking to clarify my thoughts :thinking: \r\n\r\nIf you think it'd be better to keep explicit labels #39764 can just be re-opened instead. ",
